data.jamchart_notes: First really exploratory jam of 2021 and it hints at the development of the "Ted" motif that will be come prevalent throughout the year. Back half is some great dual-guitar funk that eventually bleeds into an explosive "Bob Don."

data.jamchart_notes: A jam that Peter would write home about, two guitar Goose locks in immediately. Peter finds a nasty repeating hook at 14:20 that band centers and builds around. In 19th minute, band cools jam down and a few minutes later Peter begins soloing melodically and beautifully on the keys. Goose slowly and magically builds around Pete once again and finishes in gorgeous fashion.

Peter goes crazy on this "Arrow": synthy dreaminess, marimba dance style jamming, helicopter and alarm horn background effects, subtle voice drops (woo’s?), double guitar darkness. Once he shifts back to melodic keys you know final drive to peak is coming (and it delivers!).

data.jamchart_notes: Standard fare until the last five minutes or so, when the band breaks into some terrifyingly evil improv. Layers of dark textures thanks to Peter's synths and clav while Rick opts for some more laid-back riffing. One of the best segments of the tour.

data.jamchart_notes: This lengthy "Arrow" takes its time to leave the bow, but, once it does, soars high and true. The band pulls every trick from the quiver, starting with juicy vintage vibes, moving into interpolated Eurythmics-style synth work, and culminating in a punchy motif in which Rick masterfully synthesizes angular phrasing and blissy peaks.

data.jamchart_notes: Goose slows things down lulling the crowd into a false sense of comfort and safety. Peter begins shooting soothing space lasers and soon the Fox Theatre is being lifted into the dark skies, as the music slowly morphing into an extra-terrestrial summoning. Thick and evil music pours forth from the stage to swallow the crowd during this absolute all-time jam.

data.jamchart_notes: Peter hangs back for most of the jam on subtle OB-6 work, which gives Rick and Cotter the room they need to DOMINATE. A propulsive and dark theme emerges with Rick on nonstop momentum, using Cotter's full-steam-ahead groove to destroy everything in his path. Blasts back into a high-energy finish.

data.jamchart_notes: Equal parts vibesy vibes, angular reverse delay, Big T fulcrum lines, cyclonic tribal toms, digital sauce, and staccato guitar attack, all culminating in a plucked-from-thin-air melody for Rick's closing solo, permuted several times before dissolving into the composed ending. Sultrily stirred.

data.jamchart_notes: A thick, grimy soundscape with heavily distorted vibes, Trevor in beast mode, Rick Marshall stack-like overdriven vamping, and a handful of perfectly-placed Jebb bass bombs. A sonic full-frontal assault. If War on Drugs covered “Arrow,” it would sound like this.

Calls back to the 12/13/24 "Hungersite" in the way that Peter builds a repetitive soaring riff on clav for the first part. The band hits a beautiful peak before cooling into a minute of moody play akin to Ted Tapes cut "Arrokoth" before moving on to "Interlude II."

Auspicious opener that is standard fare until the final segment, where the band descends into a patient, clav-dominated space. Airy melodies take over for several minutes as the band gradually finds their way into "Bob Don."

data.shownotes: Moby was played for the first time since February 13, 2025 (58 shows). Before the show, creepy music played and technical difficulties ensued marked by Loomis calling over the PA, suddenly the entire crowd was sent through the veil much like the 4 lads from the promo video. Upon landing in a new world Barnaby Glimpse welcomed his new friends to his Show Upon Time. Following his opening monologue, the band kicked into a Menagerie set marked by animal balloons, animal puppets and animal performers. Carnies also passed out Goose branded Animal Crackers. After Animal, Barnaby reappeared on stage for a brief monologue. During the encore, members slowly left the stage, Cotter first after Jed, then Stu and Trevor after Master & a Hound. Peter left during Sugar Mountain. At the end of the song, Rick shut off the lamp on his rig and left the stage.
